# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: motor-drivers-hbridge
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] An inrush current limiter is a device or combination of devices used to limit inrush current.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] More complex solutions using active components can be used when more straightforward options are unsuitable.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] Some electronic circuits employ active current limiting since a fuse may not protect solid-state devices.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] One style of current-limiting circuit is shown in the image.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] The schematic represents a simple protection mechanism used in regulated DC supplies and class-AB power amplifiers.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] Rsens is the load current sensing device.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] Q2 is the protection transistor, which turns on as soon as the voltage across Rsens becomes about 0.65 V.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] This voltage is determined by the value of Rsens and the load current through it (Iload).
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] When Q2 turns on, it removes the base current from Q1, thereby reducing the collector current of Q1, which is nearly the load current.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] Thus, Rsens fixes the maximum current to a value given by 0.65/Rsens.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] For example, if Rsens = 0.33 Ω, the current is limited to about 2 A even if Rload becomes a short (and Vo becomes zero).
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] Further, this power dissipation will remain as long as the overload exists, which means that the devices must be capable of withstanding it for a substantial period.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] This power dissipation will be substantially less than if no current-limiting circuit had been provided.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] In this technique, beyond the current limit, the output voltage will decrease to a value depending on the current limit and load resistance.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] To reduce the heat that must be dissipated by the pass devices under a short-circuit, *foldback* current limiting is used, which reduces current in the short-circuit case.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] Under a short circuit, where the output voltage has reduced to zero, the current is typically limited to a small fraction of the maximum current.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] The prime purpose of foldback current limiting in linear power supplies is to keep the output transistor within its safe power dissipation limit.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] A linear regulator dissipates the difference between input and output voltages as heat.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] Under overload conditions, the output voltage falls, so the difference becomes larger, thus increasing dissipation.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] Foldback helps to keep the output transistor within its safe operating area under fault and overload conditions.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] Foldback also significantly reduces the power dissipation in the load in fault conditions, which can reduce the risks of fire and heat damage.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] Many power supplies employ constant current limiting protection; foldback goes one step further by linearly reducing the output current limit as output voltage decreases.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] However, it adds complexity to the power supply.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] It can trigger *lockout* conditions with non-ohmic devices that draw a constant current independent of the supply voltage (such as op-amps).
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] A foldback current limiter may also employ a transient delay to avoid lockout and limit localized heating at the short circuit.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] The safety benefit of reducing the power delivered to a short circuit in the load is proportional to the operating current limit.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] Foldback current limiting is most likely to be found in a switch-mode power supply when it is a component in a product that is independently certified to meet regional safety standards.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] An issue with the previous circuit is that Q1 will not be saturated unless its base is biased about 0.5 volts above Vcc.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] These circuits operate more efficiently from a single (Vcc) supply.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] In both circuits, R1 allows Q1 to turn on and pass voltage and current to the load.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] When the current through R_sense exceeds the design limit, Q2 turns on, which in turn begins to turn off Q1, thus limiting the load current.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] The optional component R2 protects Q2 in the event of a short-circuited load.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] When Vcc is at least a few volts, a MOSFET can be used for Q1 for lower dropout voltage.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/current-limiting] Due to its simplicity, this circuit is sometimes used as a current source for high-power LEDs.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] A **flyback diode** (also called **freewheeling diode**) is any diode connected across an inductor used to eliminate flyback, which is the sudden voltage spike seen across an inductive load when its supply current is suddenly reduced or interrupted.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] It is used in circuits in which inductive loads are controlled by switches, and in switching power supplies and inverters.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] Flyback circuits have been used since 1930 and were refined starting in 1950 for use in television receivers.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] The word *flyback* comes from the horizontal movement of the electron beam in a cathode ray tube, because the beam flew back to begin the next horizontal line.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] This diode is known by many other names, such as snubber diode, commutating diode, freewheeling diode, suppressor diode, clamp diode, or catch diode.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] 1 shows an inductor connected to a battery - a constant voltage source.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] The resistor represents the small static resistance of the inductor's wire windings.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] When the switch is closed, the voltage from the battery is applied to the inductor, causing current from the battery's positive terminal to flow down through the inductor and resistor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] The increase in current causes a back EMF (voltage) across the inductor due to Faraday's law of induction which opposes the change in current.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] As the current rises, more voltage is dropped across the resistor and less across the inductor, until the current reaches a steady value of $I=V_{B}/R$ with all the battery voltage across the resistance and none across the inductance.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] However, the current drops rapidly when the switch is opened in Fig.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] The inductor resists the drop in current by developing a very large induced voltage of polarity in the opposite direction of the battery, positive at the lower end of the inductor and negative at the upper end.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] This voltage pulse, sometimes called the inductive "kick", which can be much larger than the battery voltage, appears across the switch contacts.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] It causes electrons to jump the air gap between the contacts, causing a momentary electric arc to develop across the contacts as the switch is opened.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] The arc continues until the energy stored in the inductor's magnetic field is dissipated as heat in the arc.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] The arc can damage the switch contacts, causing pitting and burning, eventually destroying them.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] If a transistor is used to switch the current, such as switching power supplies, the high reverse voltage can destroy the transistor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] To prevent the inductive voltage pulse on turnoff, a diode is connected across the inductor, as shown in Fig.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] The diode doesn't conduct current while the switch is closed because it is reverse-biased by the battery voltage, so it doesn't interfere with the normal operation of the circuit.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] However, when the switch is opened, the induced voltage across the inductor of opposite polarity forward biases the diode, and it conducts current, limiting the voltage across the inductor and thus preventing the arc from forming at the switch.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] The inductor and diode momentarily form a loop or circuit powered by the stored energy in the inductor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] This circuit supplies a current path to the inductor to replace the current from the battery, so the inductor current does not drop abruptly and does not develop a high voltage.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] The voltage across the inductor is limited to the forward voltage of the diode, around 0.7 - 1.5V.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] This "freewheeling" or "flyback" current through the diode and inductor decreases slowly to zero as the magnetic energy in the inductor is dissipated as heat in the series resistance of the windings.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] This may take a few milliseconds in a small inductor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] Oscilloscope trace showing inductive voltage spike in solenoid connected to a 24 VDC power supply.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] (50 V / division on the left, 1 V / division on the right).
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] These images show the voltage spike and its elimination through the use of a flyback diode (1N4007).
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] In this case, the inductor is a solenoid connected to a 24V DC power supply.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] Each waveform was taken using a digital oscilloscope set to trigger when the voltage across the inductor dipped below zero.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] **Note the different scaling:** left image 50V/division, right image 1V/division.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] In Figure 1, the voltage as measured across the switch, bounces/spikes to around -300 V.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] In Figure 2, a flyback diode was added in antiparallel with the solenoid.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] Instead of spiking to -300 V, the flyback diode only allows approximately -1.4 V of potential to be built up (-1.4 V is a combination of the forward bias of the 1N4007 diode (1.1 V) and the foot of wiring separating the diode and the solenoid).
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] The waveform in Figure 2 is also smoother than the waveform in Figure 1, perhaps due to arcing at the switch for Figure 1.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] In both cases, the total time for the solenoid to discharge is a few milliseconds, though the lower voltage drop across the diode will slow relay dropout.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] When used with a DC coil relay, a flyback diode can cause delayed drop-out of the contacts when power is removed, due to the continued circulation of current in the relay coil and diode.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] When rapid opening of the contacts is important, a resistor or reverse-biased Zener diode can be placed in series with the diode to help dissipate the coil energy faster, at the expense of higher voltage at the switch.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] Schottky diodes are preferred in flyback diode applications for switching power converters because they have the lowest forward drop (~0.2 V rather than >0.7 V for low currents) and are able to quickly respond to reverse bias (when the inductor is being re-energized).
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] They, therefore, dissipate less energy while transferring energy from the inductor to a capacitor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] According to Faraday's law of induction, if the current through an inductance changes, this inductance induces a voltage, so the current will flow as long as there is energy in the magnetic field.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] If the current can only flow through the air, the voltage is so high that the air conducts.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] That is why in mechanically switched circuits, the near-instantaneous dissipation which occurs without a flyback diode is often observed as an arc across the opening mechanical contacts.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] Energy is dissipated in this arc primarily as intense heat, which causes undesirable premature erosion of the contacts.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] Another way to dissipate energy is through electromagnetic radiation.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] Similarly, for non-mechanical solid-state switching (i.e., a transistor), large voltage drops across an unactivated solid-state switch can destroy the component in question (either instantaneously or through accelerated wear and tear).
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] Some energy is also lost from the system as a whole and from the arc as a broad spectrum of electromagnetic radiation, in the form of radio waves and light.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] These radio waves can cause undesirable clicks and pops on nearby radio receivers.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] To minimise the antenna-like radiation of this electromagnetic energy from wires connected to the inductor, the flyback diode should be connected as physically close to the inductor as practicable.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] This approach also minimises those parts of the circuit that are subject to an unwanted high-voltage — a good engineering practice.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] We observe that the current will decrease faster if the resistance is high, such as with air.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] Now if we open the switch with the diode in place, we only need to consider *L*1, *R*1 and *D*1.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] We can calculate the time it needs to switch off by determining for which t it is *I*(*t*) = 0.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] Flyback diodes are commonly used when semiconductor devices switch inductive loads off: in relay drivers, H-bridge motor drivers, and so on.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] A switched-mode power supply also exploits this effect, but the energy is not dissipated to heat and is instead used to pump a packet of additional charge into a capacitor, in order to supply power to a load.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] When the inductive load is a relay, the flyback diode can noticeably delay the release of the relay by keeping the coil current flowing longer.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] A resistor in series with the diode will make the circulating current decay faster at the drawback of an increased reverse voltage.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] A zener diode in series but with reverse polarity with regard to the flyback diode has the same properties, albeit with a fixed reverse voltage increase.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/freewheeling-diode] Both the transistor voltages and the resistor or zener diode power ratings should be checked in this case.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] An **H-bridge** is an electronic circuit that switches the polarity of a voltage applied to a load.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] These circuits are often used in robotics and other applications to allow DC motors to run forwards or backwards.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] The name is derived from its common schematic diagram representation, with four switching elements configured as the branches of a letter "H" and the load connected as the cross-bar.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] Most DC-to-AC converters (power inverters), most AC/AC converters, the DC-to-DC push–pull converter, isolated DC-to-DC converter most motor controllers, and many other kinds of power electronics use H-bridges.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] In particular, a bipolar stepper motor is almost always driven by a motor controller containing two H-bridges.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] H-bridges are available as integrated circuits, or can be built from discrete components.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] The term *H-bridge* is derived from the typical graphical representation of such a circuit.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] An H-bridge is built with four switches (solid-state or mechanical).
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] When the switches S1 and S4 (according to the first figure) are closed (and S2 and S3 are open) a positive voltage is applied across the motor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] By opening S1 and S4 switches and closing S2 and S3 switches, this voltage is reversed, allowing reverse operation of the motor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] Using the nomenclature above, the switches S1 and S2 should never be closed at the same time, as this would cause a short circuit on the input voltage source.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] The same applies to the switches S3 and S4.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] This condition is known as shoot-through.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] An H-bridge is used to supply power to a two terminal device.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] By proper arrangement of the switches, the polarity of the power to the device can be changed.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] Two examples are discussed below: DC motor Driver, and transformer for a switching regulator.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] Note that not every switching configuration is safe; the "short"(see below in "DC motor driver" section) cases are dangerous to the power source and to the switches.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] Changing the polarity of the power supply to DC motor is used to change the direction of rotation.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] Apart from changing the rotation direction, the H-bridge can provide additional operation modes, "brake" and "free run until frictional stop".
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] The H-bridge arrangement is generally used to reverse the polarity/direction of the motor, but can also be used to 'brake' the motor, where the motor comes to a sudden stop when the motor's terminals are connected together.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] By connecting its terminals, the motor's kinetic energy is consumed rapidly in form of electrical current and causes the motor to slow down.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] Another case allows the motor to coast to a stop, as the motor is effectively disconnected from the circuit.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] The following table summarizes operation, with S1-S4 corresponding to the diagram above.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] In the table below, "1" is used to represent "on" state of the switch, "0" to represent the "off" state.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] Typical primary coil driver is to simply replace the two terminals of the DC motor by the two terminals of the primary coil.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] The switching current in the primary coil turns electrical energy into magnetic energy and transfers back to ac electrical energy in the secondary coil.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] One way to build an H-bridge is to use an array of relays from a relay board.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] A "double pole double throw" (DPDT) relay can generally achieve the same electrical functionality as an H-bridge (considering the usual function of the device).
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] However a semiconductor-based H-bridge would be preferable to the relay where a smaller physical size, high speed switching, or low driving voltage (or low driving power) is needed, or where the wearing out of mechanical parts is undesirable.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] Another configuration is to have a DPDT relay to set the direction of current flow and a transistor to enable the current flow.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] This can extend the relay life, as the relay will be switched while the transistor is off and thereby there is no current flow.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] It also enables the use of PWM switching to control the current level.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] A solid-state H-bridge is typically constructed using opposite polarity devices, such as PNP bipolar junction transistors (BJT) or P-channel MOSFETs connected to the high voltage bus and NPN BJTs or N-channel MOSFETs connected to the low voltage bus.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] The most efficient MOSFET designs use N-channel MOSFETs on both the high side and low side because they typically have a third of the ON resistance of P-channel MOSFETs.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] This requires a more complex design since the gates of the high side MOSFETs must be driven positive with respect to the DC supply rail.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] Many integrated circuit MOSFET gate drivers include a charge pump within the device to achieve this.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] Alternatively, a switched-mode power supply DC–DC converter can be used to provide isolated ('floating') supplies to the gate drive circuitry.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] A multiple-output flyback converter is well-suited to this application.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] Another method for driving MOSFET-bridges is the use of a specialised transformer known as a GDT (gate drive transformer), which gives the isolated outputs for driving the upper FETs gates.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] The transformer core is usually a ferrite toroid, with 1:1 or 4:9 winding ratio.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] However, this method can only be used with high frequency signals.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] The design of the transformer is also very important, as the leakage inductance should be minimized, or cross conduction may occur.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] The outputs of the transformer are usually clamped by Zener diodes, because high voltage spikes could destroy the MOSFET gates.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] A common variation of this circuit uses just the two transistors on one side of the load, similar to a class AB amplifier.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] Such a configuration is called a "half bridge".
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] It acts as an electronic toggle switch, the half bridge is not able to switch polarity of the voltage applied to the load.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] The half bridge is used in some switched-mode power supplies that use synchronous rectifiers and in switching amplifiers.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] The half-H-bridge type is commonly abbreviated to "Half-H" to distinguish it from full ("Full-H") H-bridges.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] Another common variation, adding a third 'leg' to the bridge, creates a three-phase inverter.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] The three-phase inverter is the core of any AC motor drive.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] A further variation is the half-controlled bridge, where the low-side switching device on one side of the bridge, and the high-side switching device on the opposite side of the bridge, are each replaced with diodes.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] This eliminates the shoot-through failure mode, and is commonly used to drive variable or switched reluctance machines and actuators where bi-directional current flow is not required.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] There are many commercially available inexpensive single and dual H-bridge packages.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] The L293x series, being technically mostly obsolete since the late 1970s due to decreased switching losses and higher speeds in more modern semiconductor products, is still found in many hobbyist circuitry.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] Few packages, like L9110, have built-in flyback diodes for back EMF protection.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] A common use of the H-bridge is an inverter.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] The arrangement is sometimes known as a single-phase bridge inverter.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] The H-bridge with a DC supply will generate a square wave voltage waveform across the load.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/h-bridge] For a purely inductive load, the current waveform would be a triangle wave, with its peak depending on the inductance, switching frequency, and input voltage.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] A **motor controller** is a device or group of devices that can coordinate in a predetermined manner the performance of an electric motor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] A motor controller might include a manual or automatic means for starting and stopping the motor, selecting forward or reverse rotation, selecting and regulating the speed, regulating or limiting the torque, and protecting against overloads and electrical faults.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Motor controllers may use electromechanical switching, or may use power electronics devices to regulate the speed and direction of a motor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Motor controllers are used with both DC motors (direct current) and AC motors (alternating current).
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] A controller includes means to connect the motor's windings to the electrical power supply, and may also include overload, over-current, and overheating protection and wiring (i.e. magnetic starter).
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] A motor controller may also supervise the motor's field circuit, or detect conditions such as low supply voltage, incorrect polarity or incorrect phase sequence, or high motor temperature.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Some motor controllers limit the inrush starting current, allowing the motor to accelerate itself and connected mechanical load more slowly than a direct connection.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Motor controllers may be manual, requiring an operator to sequence a starting switch through steps to accelerate the load, or may be fully automatic, using internal timers or current sensors to accelerate the motor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Some types of motor controllers also allow adjustment of the speed of the electric motor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] For direct-current motors, the controller may adjust the voltage applied to the motor, or adjust the current flowing in the motor's field winding.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] The physical design and packaging of motor controllers is about as varied as that of electric motors themselves.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] A wall-mounted toggle switch with suitable ratings may be all that is needed for a household ventilation fan.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Power tools and household appliances may have a trigger switch that only turns the motor on and off.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Industrial motors may be more complex controllers connected to automation systems; a factory may have a large number of motor controllers grouped in a motor control center.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Controllers for electric travelling cranes or electric vehicles may be mounted on the mobile equipment.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] The largest motor controllers are used with the pumping motors of pumped storage hydroelectric plants, and may carry ratings of tens of thousands of horsepower (kilowatts).
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Motor controllers can be manually, remotely or automatically operated.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] They may include only the means for starting and stopping the motor or they may include other functions.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Electric motors can be powered by AC or DC power sources.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] There are many type of AC and DC motors - namely brush, brushless, servo and stepper motors - depending on their mechanical construction.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] A motor controller is connected to a power source, such as a battery pack or power supply, and control circuitry in the form of analog or digital input signals.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] A small motor can be started by simply connecting it to power.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] A larger motor requires a specialized switching unit called a motor starter or motor contactor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] When energized, a direct on line (DOL) starter immediately connects the motor terminals directly to the power supply.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] In smaller sizes a motor starter is a manually operated switch; larger motors, or those requiring remote or automatic control, use magnetic contactors.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Very large motors running on medium voltage power supplies (thousands of volts) may use power circuit breakers as switching elements.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] A **direct on line** (DOL) or *across the line* starter applies the full line voltage to the motor terminals.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] This is the simplest type of motor starter.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] A DOL motor starter often contains protection devices (see below), and in some cases, condition monitoring.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Smaller sizes of direct on-line starters are manually operated; larger sizes use an electromechanical contactor to switch the motor circuit.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Solid-state direct on line starters also exist.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] A direct on line starter can be used if the high inrush current of the motor does not cause excessive voltage drop in the supply circuit.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] The maximum size of a motor allowed on a direct on line starter may be limited by the supply utility for this reason.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] For example, a utility may require rural customers to use reduced-voltage starters for motors larger than 10 kW.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] DOL starting is sometimes used to start small water pumps, compressors, fans and conveyor belts.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] In the case of an asynchronous motor, such as the 3-phase squirrel-cage motor, the motor will draw a high starting current until it has run up to full speed.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] This starting current is typically 6-7 times greater than the full load current.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] To reduce the inrush current, larger motors will have reduced-voltage starters or adjustable-speed drives in order to minimise voltage dips to the power supply.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] A reversing starter can connect the motor for rotation in either direction.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Such a starter contains two DOL circuits — one for clockwise operation and the other for counter-clockwise operation, with mechanical and electrical interlocks to prevent simultaneous closure.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] For three phase motors, this is achieved by swapping the wires connecting any two phases.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Single phase AC motors and direct-current motors often can be reversed by swapping two wires but this is not always the case.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Motor starters other than 'DOL' connect the motor through a resistance to reduce the voltage the motor coils get on start up.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] The resistance for this needs to be sized to the motor - and a quick source for a good resistance to use is another coil in the motor - i.e. series/parallel.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] In series gives a gentler start then switched to parallel for full power running.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] When this is done with three phase motors, it is commonly called a star-delta (US: Y-delta) starter.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Old star-delta starters were manually operated and often incorporated an ammeter so the person operating the starter could see when the motor was up to speed by the fact the current it was drawing had stopped decreasing.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] More modern starters have built-in timers to switch from star to delta and are set by the electrical installer of the machine.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] The machine's operator simply presses a green button once and the rest of the start procedure is automated.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] A typical starter includes protection against overload, both electrical and mechanical, and protection against 'random' starting - if, for instance, the power has been off and has just come back on.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] An acronym for this type of protection is TONVR - Thermal Overload, No Volt Release.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] It insists that the green button is pressed to start the motor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] The green button switches on a solenoid which closes a contactor (i.e. switch) to primarily power the motor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] It also powers the solenoid to keep the power turned on when the green button is released.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] In a power failure, the contactor opens turning itself and the motor off.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] The only way the motor can then be started is by pressing the green button.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] The contactor can be quickly tripped by the starter passing a very high current due to an electrical fault downstream of it in either the wiring to the motor or within the motor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] The thermal overload protection consists of a heating element on each power wire which heats a bimetallic strip.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] The hotter the strip, the more it deflects to the point it pushes a trip bar which disconnects power to the contactor solenoid, turning everything off.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Thermal overloads come in different range ratings and this should be chosen to match the motor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Within the range, they are adjustable enabling the installer to set it correctly for the given motor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] DOL gives a quick start so is used more commonly with generally smaller motors.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] It is also used on machines with an uneven load such as piston type compressors where the full power of the motor is needed to get the piston past the compression stage - the actual working stage.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Star-delta is generally used with larger motors or where either the motor is under no load at starting, very little load or a consistent load.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] It is particularly suited to motors driving machinery with heavy flywheels - to get the flywheels up to speed before the machine is engaged and driven by the flywheel.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Reduced-voltage or soft starters connect the motor to the power supply through a voltage reduction device and increases the applied voltage gradually or in steps.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Two or more contactors may be used to provide reduced voltage starting of a motor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] By using an autotransformer or a series inductance, a lower voltage is present at the motor terminals, reducing starting torque and inrush current.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Once the motor has come up to some fraction of its full-load speed, the starter switches to full voltage at the motor terminals.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Since the autotransformer or series reactor only carries the heavy motor starting current for a few seconds, the devices can be much smaller compared to continuously rated equipment.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] The transition between reduced and full voltage may be based on elapsed time, or triggered when a current sensor shows the motor current has begun to reduce.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] An autotransformer starter was patented in 1908.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Larger 3 phase induction motors can have their power reduced within the motor !
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] The motor is started 'DOL' with full voltage supplied to the field coils of the motor outer part ('stator').
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] The inner part ('rotor') has a current induced into it to once again react with the magnetic field generated by the stator.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] By breaking the rotor into parts and electrically connecting these parts to external resistances via slip rings and brushes as well as control contactors, the magnetic power of the rotor can be varied - i.e. reduced, for starting or low power running.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Although a much more complex process, it means the currents (electrical loads) being switched are significantly lower than if reducing the power to the main feed of the motor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] A third way to achieve a very smooth progressive start is to dip resistance rods into a conductive liquid (e.g. mercury) which has a layer of insulative oil on the top.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] As the rods are lowered the resistance is gradually reduced.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] A star delta starter is another type of Reduced-voltage starter in induction motor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] A star delta starter will start a motor with a star connected stator winding.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] When motor reaches about 80% of its full load speed, it will begin to run in a delta connected stator winding.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] (1) Manual Operated Star Delta Starter, (2) Automatic Star Delta.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] The manual operated star delta starter mainly consists of a TPDT switch which stands for Triple Pole Double Throw switch.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] This switch changes stator winding from star to delta.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] During starting condition stator winding is connected in the form of a star.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Now we shall see how a star delta starter reduces the starting current of a three-phase induction motor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] The above function achieved by using a power contactor and timer in automatic star delta starter.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] The automatic star delta starter is manufactured from three contactors, a timer and a thermal overload.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] The contactors are smaller than the single contactor used in a direct on line starter as they are controlling winding currents only.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] The currents through the winding are 1/root 3 (58%) of the current in the line.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] There are two contactors that are close during run, often referred to as the main contractor and the delta contactor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] These are AC3 rated at 58% of the current rating of the motor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] The third contactor is the star contactor and that only carries star current while the motor is connected in star.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] The current in star is one third of the current in delta, so this contactor can be AC3 rated at one third (33%) of the motor rating.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] The transition from star to delta can be an open transition or a closed transition.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] During open transition, the motor starter momentarily disconnects from the motor and reconnects in a delta configuration.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] In closed transition, the transition from the star to delta configuration is achieved without disconnecting the motor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] In order to achieve that, an additional three-pole contactor and three resistors are required.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] An *adjustable-speed drive* (ASD) or *variable-speed drive* (VSD) is an interconnected combination of equipment that provides a means of driving and adjusting the operating speed of a mechanical load.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] An electrical adjustable-speed drive consists of an electric motor and a speed controller or power converter plus auxiliary devices and equipment.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] In common usage, the term "drive" is often applied to just the controller.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Most modern ASDs and VSDs can also implement soft motor starting.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] An *Intelligent Motor Controller* (IMC) uses a microprocessor to control power electronic devices used for motor control.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] IMCs monitor the load on a motor and accordingly match motor torque to motor load.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] This is accomplished by reducing the voltage to the AC terminals and at the same time lowering current and kvar.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] This can provide a measure of energy efficiency improvement for motors that run under light load for a large part of the time, resulting in less heat, noise, and vibrations generated by the motor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] A starter will contain protective devices for the motor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] At a minimum this would include a thermal overload relay.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] The thermal overload is designed to open the starting circuit and thus cut the power to the motor in the event of the motor drawing too much current from the supply for an extended time.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] The overload relay has a normally closed contact which opens due to heat generated by excessive current flowing through the circuit.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Thermal overloads have a small heating device that increases in temperature as the motor running current increases.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] There are two types of thermal overload relay.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] In one type, a bimetallic strip located close to a heater deflects as the heater temperature rises until it mechanically causes the device to trip and open the circuit, cutting power to the motor should it become overloaded.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] A thermal overload will accommodate the brief high starting current of a motor while accurately protecting it from a running current overload.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] The heater coil and the action of the bi-metallic strip introduce a time delay that affords the motor time to start and settle into normal running current without the thermal overload tripping.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Thermal overloads can be manually or automatically resettable depending on their application and have an adjuster that allows them to be accurately set to the motor run current.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] A second type of thermal overload relay uses a eutectic alloy, like a solder, to retain a spring-loaded contact.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] When too much current passes through the heating element for too long a time, the alloy melts and the spring releases the contact, opening the control circuit and shutting down the motor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Since eutectic alloy elements are not adjustable, they are resistant to casual tampering but require changing the heater coil element to match the motor rated current.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Electronic digital overload relays containing a microprocessor may also be used, especially for high-value motors.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] These devices model the heating of the motor windings by monitoring the motor current.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] They can also include metering and communication functions.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Starters using magnetic contactors usually derive the power supply for the contactor coil from the same source as the motor supply.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] An auxiliary contact from the contactor is used to maintain the contactor coil energized after the start command for the motor has been released.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] If a momentary loss of supply voltage occurs, the contactor will open and not close again until a new start command is given.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] This prevents restarting of the motor after a power failure.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] This connection also provides a small degree of protection against low power supply voltage and loss of a phase.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] However, since contactor coils will hold the circuit closed with as little as 80% of normal voltage applied to the coil, this is not a primary means of protecting motors from low voltage operation.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Some devices can be added so that during a voltage drop, the device maintains the current flow that is sufficient for the hold-in coil to keep the contacts closed.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] The circuit is designed allows current for the hold-in coil for voltage sags down to 15-25% voltage.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] After the electrical power has been restored (typically after a time delay of 30 to 60 seconds), then the time sequences of the automatic restarts of multiple motors are set to automatically begin.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Without a time sequenced schedule, any attempt to restart many motors simultaneously could lead to partial or total site wide power failure.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Servo controllers are a wide category of motor control.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Servo controllers use position feedback to close the control loop.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] This is commonly implemented with position encoders, resolvers, and Hall effect sensors to directly measure the rotor's position.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Other position feedback methods measure the back EMF in the undriven coils to infer the rotor position, or detect the Kick-Back voltage transient (spike) that is generated whenever the power to a coil is instantaneously switched off.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] These are therefore often called "sensorless" control methods.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] A servo may be controlled using pulse-width modulation (PWM).
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] How long the pulse remains high (typically between 1 and 2 milliseconds) determines where the motor will try to position itself.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Another control method is pulse and direction.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] A stepper, or stepping, motor is a synchronous, brushless, high pole count, polyphase motor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Control is usually, but not exclusively, done open loop, *i.e.*, the rotor position is assumed to follow a controlled rotating field.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Because of this, precise positioning with steppers is simpler and cheaper than closed loop controls.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] Modern stepper controllers drive the motor with much higher voltages than the motor nameplate rated voltage, and limit current through chopping.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/motor-controller] The usual setup is to have a positioning controller, known as an *indexer*, sending step and direction pulses to a separate higher voltage drive circuit which is responsible for commutation and current limiting.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] PWM is useful for controlling the average power or amplitude delivered by an electrical signal.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The average value of voltage (and current) fed to the load is controlled by switching the supply between 0 and 100% at a rate faster than it takes the load to change significantly.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The longer the switch is on, the higher the total power supplied to the load.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Along with maximum power point tracking (MPPT), it is one of the primary methods of controlling the output of solar panels to that which can be utilized by a battery.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] PWM is particularly suited for running inertial loads such as motors, which are not as easily affected by this discrete switching.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The goal of PWM is to control a load; however, the PWM switching frequency must be selected carefully in order to smoothly do so.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The PWM switching frequency can vary greatly depending on load and application.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Choosing a switching frequency that is too high for the application may cause premature failure of mechanical control components, despite getting smooth control of the load.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Selecting a switching frequency that is too low for the application causes oscillations in the load.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The main advantage of PWM is that power loss in the switching devices is very low.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] When a switch is off, there is practically no current, and when it is on and power is being transferred to the load, there is almost no voltage drop across the switch.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Power loss, being the product of voltage and current, is thus in both cases close to zero.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] PWM also works well with digital controls, which, because of their on/off nature, can easily set the needed duty cycle.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] PWM has also been used in certain communication systems where its duty cycle has been used to convey information over a communications channel.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The term *duty cycle* describes the proportion of 'on' time to the regular interval or 'period' of time; a low duty cycle corresponds to low power, because the power is off for most of the time.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Duty cycle is expressed in percent, 100% being fully on.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] When a digital signal is on half of the time and off the other half of the time, the digital signal has a duty cycle of 50% and resembles a "square" wave.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] When a digital signal spends more time in the on state than the off state, it has a duty cycle of >50%.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] When a digital signal spends more time in the off state than the on state, it has a duty cycle of <50%.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The Corliss steam engine was patented in 1849.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] It used pulse-width modulation to control the intake valve of a steam engine cylinder.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] A centrifugal governor was used to provide automatic feedback.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Some machines (such as a sewing machine motor) require partial or variable power.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] In the past, control (such as in a sewing machine's foot pedal) was implemented by use of a rheostat connected in series with the motor to adjust the amount of current flowing through the motor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] It was an inefficient scheme, as this also wasted power as heat in the resistor element of the rheostat, but tolerable because the total power was low.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] While the rheostat was one of several methods of controlling power (see autotransformers and Variac for more info), a low-cost and efficient power switching and adjustment method was yet to be found.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] This mechanism also needed to be able to drive motors for fans, pumps and robotic servomechanisms, and needed to be compact enough to interface with lamp dimmers.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] PWM emerged as a solution for this complex problem.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] PWM telecommunications systems were invented just prior to the start of World War II, but at that time time-division multiplexing was already in use and there were only experimental PWM systems.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] This changed with the introduction of the cavity magnetron in 1940, which could produce pulses of microwave frequency energy but could not vary its frequency or precisely control its amplitude.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] A PWM encoder was used to trigger a magnetron in the British Army's Wireless Set Number 10, which provided long-distance telephone relay, up to 80 kilometres (50 mi).
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] V. company had designed an optical scanning system for variable area film soundtrack which used PWM while it was scanning the optical audio track transversely with a thin light beam.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The electronics then evaluated the threshold between exposed (non-translucent) and unexposed (translucent) parts of the audio track.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The proposed system was to reduce noise when playing a film soundtrack.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] One early application of PWM was in the Sinclair X10, a 10 W audio amplifier available in kit form in the 1960s.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] At around the same time, PWM started to be used in AC motor control.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] In the mid-1970s, early automotive applications of pulse-width modulation (PWM) were developed in the UK by Associated Engineering Developments Ltd (AED).
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Engineers Norman Hunt and John Noddings designed systems that used pulse-width modulated electrical signals to control high-speed solenoid valves.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] By altering the signal's duty cycle, the system could vary hydraulic and pneumatic pressure instead of just turning a solenoid valve fully open or fully closed.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] This technology was commercialised through AED's subsidiary company, Econocruise Ltd, based in Rugby, Warwickshire.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The company used these modulated solenoid valves in pneumatic assemblies to control throttle actuators, supplying cruise control systems for luxury passenger cars and PWM speed limiters for heavy commercial trucks and buses.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] This latter expression can be fairly simplified in many cases where $y_{\text{min}}=0$ as ${\bar {y}}=D\cdot y_{\text{max}}$ .
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] From this, the average value of the signal ( ${\bar {y}}$ ) is directly dependent on the duty cycle D.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] However, by varying (i.e. modulating) the duty cycle (and possibly also the period), the following more advanced pulse-width modulated waves allow variation of the average value of the waveform.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The intersective method is a simple way to generate a PWM output signal (magenta in above figure) with fixed period and varying duty cycle is by using a comparator to switch the PWM output state when the input waveform (red) intersects with a sawtooth or a triangle waveform (blue).
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Many digital circuits can generate PWM signals (e.g., many microcontrollers have PWM outputs).
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] They normally use a counter that increments periodically (it is connected directly or indirectly to the clock of the circuit) and is reset at the end of every period of the PWM.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] When the counter value is more than the reference value, the PWM output changes state from high to low (or low to high).
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] This technique is referred to as **time proportioning,** particularly as **time-proportioning control** – which *proportion* of a fixed cycle time is spent in the high state.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The incremented and periodically reset counter is the discrete version of the intersecting method's sawtooth.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The analog comparator of the intersecting method becomes a simple integer comparison between the current counter value and the digital (possibly digitized) reference value.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The duty cycle can only be varied in discrete steps, as a function of the counter resolution.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] However, a high-resolution counter can provide quite satisfactory performance.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The resulting spectra (of the three alignments) are similar.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Each contains a DC component, a base sideband containing the modulating signal, and phase modulated carriers at each harmonic of the frequency of the pulse.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The amplitudes of the harmonic groups are restricted by a $\sin x/x$ envelope (sinc function) and extend to infinity.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The infinite bandwidth is caused by the nonlinear operation of the pulse-width modulator.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] In consequence, a digital PWM suffers from aliasing distortion that significantly reduce its applicability for modern communication systems.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] By limiting the bandwidth of the PWM kernel, aliasing effects can be avoided.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] On the contrary, delta modulation and delta-sigma modulation are random processes that produces a continuous spectrum without distinct harmonics.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] While intersective PWM uses a fixed period but a varying duty cycle, the period of delta and delta-sigma modulated PWMs varies in addition to their duty cycle.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Delta modulation produces a PWM signal (magenta in the above figure) which changes state whenever its integral (blue) hits the limits (green) surrounding the input (red).
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Asynchronous (i.e., unclocked) delta-sigma modulation produces a PWM output (blue in bottom plot) which is subtracted from the input signal (green in top plot) to form an error signal (blue in top plot).
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] This error is integrated (magenta in the middle plot).
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] When the integral of the error exceeds the limits (the upper and lower grey lines in the middle plot), the PWM output changes state.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] By integrating the difference of the error with the input signal, delta-sigma modulation shapes noise of the resulting spectrum is more concentrated in higher frequencies above the input signal's band.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Direct torque control is a method used to control AC motors.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] It is closely related to the delta modulation (see above).
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Motor torque and magnetic flux are estimated and these are controlled to stay within their hysteresis bands by turning on a new combination of the device's semiconductor switches each time either signal tries to deviate out of its band.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The process of PWM conversion is non-linear, and it is generally supposed that low-pass filter signal recovery is imperfect for PWM.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] In electronics, many modern microcontrollers (MCUs) integrate **PWM controllers** exposed to external pins as peripheral devices under firmware control.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] These are commonly used for direct current (DC) motor control in robotics, switched-mode power supply regulation, and other applications.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The type of PWM controller found in MCUs is based on a digital counter.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] In the basic output mode, the counter is compared against a threshold level to determine whether a signal should be output.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] As a result, the threshold level determines the duty cycle.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] (This is a digital version of the intersective method from above.) Some PWMs include a way to control the period/frequency, either a configurable clock divider or a "prescaling" counter.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Many PWM controllers are also input devices: they can measure the characteristics (frequency, duty cycle) of an input PWM signal using their inbuilt counters and triggers that fire at the falling or rising edge of the input signal.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Using two edges of the same type produces the frequency/period; using two edge measurements of different types produces the "on" or "off"-duration, which when divided by period produces the duty cycle.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] PWM is used to control servomechanisms; see servo control.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The PWM output of a microcontroller is almost never used to directly drive a motor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Instead, this signal is interpreted by a motor controller, which converts it into a more accurate PWM signal for the motor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] This kind of "PWM controller" used in robotics is derived from PWM controllers used in hobby radio control vehicles.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] In telecommunications, PWM is a form of signal modulation where the widths of the pulses correspond to specific data values encoded at one end and decoded at the other.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Pulses of various lengths (the information itself) will be sent at regular intervals (the carrier frequency of the modulation).
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The inclusion of a clock signal is not necessary, as the leading edge of the data signal can be used as the clock if a small offset is added to each data value to avoid a data value with a zero length pulse.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] PWM can be used to control the amount of power delivered to a load without incurring the losses that would result from linear power delivery by resistive means.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Drawbacks to this technique are that the power drawn by the load is not constant but rather discontinuous (see Buck converter), and energy delivered to the load is not continuous either.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] However, the load may be inductive, and with a sufficiently high frequency and when necessary using additional passive electronic filters, the pulse train can be smoothed and an average analog waveform recovered.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Power flow into the load can be continuous.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Power flow from the supply is not constant and will require energy storage on the supply side in most cases.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] High frequency PWM power control systems are easily realisable with semiconductor switches.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] As explained above, almost no power is dissipated by the switch in either on or off state.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] However, during the transitions between on and off states, both voltage and current are nonzero and thus power is dissipated in the switches.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] By quickly changing the state between fully on and fully off (typically less than 100 nanoseconds), the power dissipation in the switches can be quite low compared to the power being delivered to the load.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Modern semiconductor switches such as MOSFETs or insulated-gate bipolar transistors (IGBTs) are well-suited components for high-efficiency controllers.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Frequency converters used to control AC motors may have efficiencies exceeding 98%.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Switching power supplies have lower efficiency due to low output voltage levels (often even less than 2 V for microprocessors are needed), but still more than 70–80% efficiency can be achieved.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Variable-speed computer fan controllers usually use PWM, as it is far more efficient when compared to a potentiometer or rheostat.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Light dimmers for home use employ a specific type of PWM control.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Home-use light dimmers typically include electronic circuitry that suppresses current flow during defined portions of each cycle of the AC line voltage.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Adjusting the brightness of light emitted by a light source is then merely a matter of setting at what voltage (or phase) in the AC half-cycle the dimmer begins to provide electric current to the light source (e.g. by using an electronic switch such as a triac).
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] In this case the PWM duty cycle is the ratio of the conduction time to the duration of the half AC cycle defined by the frequency of the AC line voltage (50 or 60 Hz, depending on the country).
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Some other types of light sources, such as light-emitting diodes (LEDs), however, turn on and off extremely rapidly and would perceivably flicker if supplied with low-frequency drive voltages.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Perceivable flicker effects from such rapid-response light sources can be reduced by increasing the PWM frequency.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] If the light fluctuations are sufficiently rapid (faster than the flicker fusion threshold), the human visual system can no longer resolve them, and the eye perceives the time average intensity without flicker.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] In electric cookers, continuously variable power is applied to the heating elements, such as the hob or the grill, using a device known as a simmerstat.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] This consists of a thermal oscillator running at approximately two cycles per minute, and the mechanism varies the duty cycle according to the knob setting.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The thermal time constant of the heating elements is several minutes, so that the temperature fluctuations are too small to matter in practice.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] PWM is also used in efficient voltage regulators.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] By switching the voltage to the load with the appropriate duty cycle, the output will approximate a voltage at the desired level.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The switching noise is usually filtered with an inductor and a capacitor.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] When it is lower than the desired voltage, it turns on the switch.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] When the output voltage is above the desired voltage, it turns off the switch.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] PWM techniques would typically be used to make some indicator (like an LED) *soft blink*.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The light will slowly go from dark to full intensity, and then slowly dim to dark again.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The period would be several soft blinks per second, up to several seconds for one blink.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] An indicator of this type would not disturb as much as a *hard-blinking* on/off indicator.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The indicator lamp on the Apple iBook G4, PowerBook 6,7 (2005) was of this type.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] This kind of indicator is also called *pulsing glow*, as opposed to calling it *flashing*.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Varying the duty cycle of a pulse waveform in a synthesis instrument creates useful timbral variations.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Some synthesizers have a duty-cycle trimmer for their square-wave outputs, and that trimmer can be set by ear; the 50% point (true square wave) is distinctive because even-numbered harmonics essentially disappear at 50%.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Pulse waves, usually 50%, 25%, and 12.5%, make up the soundtracks of classic video games.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The term PWM as used in sound (music) synthesis, refers to the ratio between the high and low levels being secondarily modulated with a low-frequency oscillator.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] This gives a sound effect similar to chorus or slightly detuned oscillators played together.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Class-D amplifiers produce a PWM equivalent of a lower frequency input signal that can be sent to a loudspeaker via a suitable filter network to block the carrier and recover the original lower frequency signal.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Since they switch power directly from the high supply rail and low supply rail, these amplifiers have efficiency above 90% and can be relatively compact and light, even for large power outputs.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] For a few decades, industrial and military PWM amplifiers have been in common use, often for driving servomotors.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Field-gradient coils in MRI machines are driven by relatively high-power PWM amplifiers.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Historically, a crude form of PWM has been used to play back PCM digital sound on the PC speaker, which is driven by only two voltage levels, typically 0 and 5 V.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The Sega 32X uses PWM to play sample-based sound in its games.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] This method is used in the SACD format, and reproduction of the encoded audio signal is essentially similar to the method used in class-D amplifiers.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] SPWM (sine–triangle pulse-width modulation) signals are used in solar inverter design.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] These switching signals are fed to the FETs that are used in the device.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] The device's efficiency depends on the harmonic content of the PWM signal.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] There is much research on eliminating unwanted harmonics and improving the fundamental strength, some of which involves using a modified carrier signal instead of a classic sawtooth signal in order to decrease power losses and improve efficiency.
[src:motor-drivers-hbridge/pulse-width-modulation] Another common application is in robotics where PWM signals are used to control the speed of the robot by controlling the motors.
